  <h1>Automotive Paint Booth Environmental Control</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">
    MSc thesis focused on environmental control for electrostatic application
    of solvent-based paint in an automotive paint booth.
  </p>
</header>

<section>
  <h2>Project Overview</h2>

  <div class="skills">
    <p><strong>Context:</strong> MSc thesis developed at Toyota Caetano Portugal, focused on environmental control for the electrostatic application of solvent-based paint in an automotive paint booth.</p>
    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> The process required a structured engineering approach to diagnose environmental instability, define control requirements and assess the feasibility of improved monitoring and control logic for temperature and humidity.</p>
    <p><strong>My Role:</strong> I defined the project methodology, performed the AS-IS diagnosis, used FMEA, SPC, measurements, observations and operator interviews, developed the requirements for environmental control, and built a Simulink/Simscape simulation to assess the feasibility of the sensor architecture and burner/humidifier control logic.</p>
    <p><strong>Duration:</strong> MSc thesis project, developed during my final year of Mechanical Engineering.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools:</strong> Simulink, Simscape, FMEA, SPC, process mapping, requirements definition, sensor architecture, control logic, industrial observations and technical interviews.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Engineering Approach</h2>

  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card">
      <span>Step 1</span>
      <h3>AS-IS Diagnosis</h3>
      <p>Analysed the existing process, environmental measurements, system limitations and operational constraints.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <span>Step 2</span>
      <h3>Risk Prioritisation</h3>
      <p>Used FMEA and engineering reasoning to identify high-priority failure modes affecting environmental control.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <span>Step 3</span>
      <h3>TO-BE Requirements</h3>
      <p>Defined monitoring, sensor, alarm, control and operator-response requirements for improved process stability.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <span>Step 4</span>
      <h3>Simulation-Based Assessment</h3>
      <p>Built Simulink/Simscape models to assess burner and humidifier control logic for environmental stabilisation.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

